## Why Representations?

Almost every system in the prior reading group sessions assumed it could already *see* audio in a useful form. DDSP took pitch and loudness as input. The transcription models took mel-spectrograms. Music generation models like VampNet took discrete audio tokens. None of them learned, from scratch, what audio *means*; they were each handed a representation and asked to do work on top of it. This session is about the layer underneath: how a model learns a representation in the first place, and what choices it makes about what to preserve.

We're working through three papers that span two paradigms. **CLAP** &mdash; **C**ontrastive **L**anguage-**A**udio **P**retraining &mdash; is the audio-side port of the CLIP recipe: pair an audio encoder with a text encoder and train them to agree on which (audio, caption) pairs go together. We cover *two* CLAP papers, the [original Microsoft CLAP (Elizalde et al., 2022)](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2206.04769) and [LAION-CLAP (Wu et al., 2023)](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2211.06687) which scaled it up by an order of magnitude, because their differences are instructive about what scale and engineering buy you on top of a fixed objective. **MERT** &mdash; **M**usic und**ER**standing model with large-scale self-supervised **T**raining &mdash; [Li et al., 2024](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2306.00107) takes the opposite approach: learn from audio alone, hide chunks of the signal, predict what was hidden, no language anywhere in the loop. CLAP yields representations that are *describable* (queryable with a natural-language sentence); MERT yields representations that are *characterizable* (they encode pitch, harmony, and timbre as features for downstream tasks, but cannot be queried in words). Both are useful; the design choices are revealing.

<Callout type="definition" label="Representation learning">
	The task of training a network to produce vectors (embeddings) that capture the structure of an input modality, without committing to any one downstream task. A good representation makes many downstream tasks easy: classification, retrieval, generation conditioning, similarity search. The hard question is what "good" means in the absence of a specific objective.
</Callout>

<Callout type="gotcha" label="There is no neutral representation">
	Every representation embeds the assumptions of its training signal. CLAP embeddings cluster by what people <em>say</em> about audio (genre labels, mood words, instrument names) because that is what the captions contain. MERT embeddings cluster by acoustic and harmonic structure because the masked-prediction task rewards capturing those features. Neither is wrong; they answer different questions, and the choice of representation pre-decides the downstream system.
</Callout>

