				<line x1="24" y1="22" x2="44" y2="30" stroke="#1a9e8f" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="2 1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
				<line x1="76" y1="22" x2="56" y2="30" stroke="#e07020" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="2 1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
				<!-- Audio input arrow -->
				<line x1="50" y1="62" x2="50" y2="52" stroke="#dde0e6" stroke-width="1"/>
				<polygon points="47,54 50,49 53,54" fill="#dde0e6"/>
				<text x="50" y="70" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="6" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif">masked audio</text>
			</svg>
		</div>
		<div class="concept-text">
			<h4 style="color: var(--violet)">Dual Teachers</h4>
			<p>MERT's central design choice: one teacher signal is not enough for music. The acoustic teacher (EnCodec RVQ indices) captures timbre and texture but is pitch-agnostic; the musical teacher (CQT) captures pitch and harmonic relationships but ignores fine acoustic detail. Training the encoder to reconstruct both forces it to preserve information that either teacher alone would discard. This is the paper's principal contribution over a straightforward HuBERT-on-music port.</p>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

<Callout type="insight" label="Two ways to supervise representation">
	CLAP and MERT illustrate the two dominant strategies for self-supervised / weakly supervised representation learning. <strong>Cross-modal contrastive</strong> (CLIP-style): use a second modality that is cheap to scrape (text, in this case) as the supervisory signal, and align across modalities. <strong>Masked prediction</strong> (BERT/HuBERT-style): hide part of the input, predict it from context, no second modality needed. The first gives you language hooks; the second gives you data efficiency and avoids caption distribution bias.
</Callout>

## CLAP: A Technique With Several Implementations

"CLAP" names a *technique* &mdash; **C**ontrastive **L**anguage-**A**udio **P**retraining &mdash; before it names any one paper. The technique is the CLIP recipe ported to audio: pair an audio encoder with a text encoder, project both into a shared vector space, train with the symmetric InfoNCE loss so that matched (audio, caption) pairs land near each other and mismatched pairs land apart. At least two notable implementations exist, and we'll walk through both before getting into the math, because they make the same big idea concrete in revealingly different ways.

### Two notable implementations

<div class="implementations-grid">
	<div class="impl-card impl-ms">
		<div class="impl-header">
			<div class="impl-title">Microsoft CLAP</div>
			<div class="impl-sub">Elizalde et al., 2022 &middot; <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2206.04769" target="_blank" rel="noopener">arXiv:2206.04769</a></div>
		</div>
		<dl class="impl-spec">
			<dt>Audio encoder</dt><dd>CNN14 from PANN &middot; 80.8M params &middot; 2048-dim output</dd>
			<dt>Text encoder</dt><dd>BERT-base uncased &middot; 110M params &middot; 768-dim [CLS]</dd>
			<dt>Shared space</dt><dd>1024-dim via 2 learnable projections</dd>
			<dt>Training data</dt><dd><strong>~128K pairs</strong> from FSD50K, ClothoV2, AudioCaps, MACS</dd>
			<dt>Schedule</dt><dd>40 epochs, Adam(1e&minus;3), batch 32&ndash;768, audio = 5s @ 44.1kHz</dd>
			<dt>Temperature</dt><dd>Learnable, initialized to 0.007 (very low &rarr; sharp softmax)</dd>
			<dt>Audio length</dt><dd>Fixed 5-second clips</dd>
		</dl>
		<div class="impl-tag">original &middot; coined the name for audio</div>
	</div>
	<div class="impl-card impl-laion">
		<div class="impl-header">
			<div class="impl-title">LAION-CLAP</div>
			<div class="impl-sub">Wu et al., 2023 &middot; <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.06687" target="_blank" rel="noopener">arXiv:2211.06687</a></div>
		</div>
		<dl class="impl-spec">
			<dt>Audio encoder</dt><dd>HTSAT (hierarchical audio Transformer) &middot; 768-dim &middot; (PANN-14 evaluated as alternative)</dd>
			<dt>Text encoder</dt><dd>RoBERTa-base, 768-dim &middot; (BERT &amp; CLIP tower also tried, RoBERTa wins)</dd>
			<dt>Shared space</dt><dd>512-dim via 2-layer MLPs, L2-normalized</dd>
			<dt>Training data</dt><dd><strong>~2.5M pairs</strong> &middot; LAION-Audio-630K + AudioCaps/Clotho + 1.9M AudioSet via K2C</dd>
			<dt>Schedule</dt><dd>45 epochs, Adam(1e&minus;4), batch 768 &rarr; 2,304 &rarr; 4,608 by scale, audio = 10s @ 48kHz</dd>
			<dt>Temperature</dt><dd>Learnable, log-space (the codebase inherits CLIP's <code>log(1/0.07)</code> default; not pinned in the paper)</dd>
			<dt>Audio length</dt><dd>Variable via Attention Feature Fusion</dd>
		</dl>
		<div class="impl-tag">scaled-up &middot; most-used in downstream systems today</div>
	</div>
</div>

<Callout type="insight" label="Same recipe, different engineering">
	Both papers solve the same problem with the same training objective (symmetric InfoNCE). The differences are <strong>encoder choice</strong> (CNN14+BERT vs. HTSAT+RoBERTa), <strong>scale</strong> (~128K pairs of clean captions vs. ~2.5M pairs including synthetically captioned AudioSet), and the engineering needed to <strong>cope with that scale</strong> (Feature Fusion for variable-length audio, Keyword-to-Caption augmentation for label-only datasets). The InfoNCE math &mdash; and the embedding geometry that results &mdash; is identical. So if you understand one, you understand the other; the rest is design choices.
</Callout>

The walkthrough below uses LAION-CLAP's specifics where the engineering diverges (because Feature Fusion and K2C are LAION-only), but the loss-function math and the geometric intuition apply equally to both. After training, the encoders from either model are useful in isolation: the audio encoder becomes a general-purpose feature extractor, and the joint geometry enables zero-shot classification and retrieval.

### The symmetric InfoNCE loss, line by line

For a batch of <span class="math-it">N</span> matched pairs, let <span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>a</sup></span>, <span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>t</sup></span> &isin; &#x211D;<sup>512</sup> be the unit-normalized audio and text embeddings. Because they live on the unit sphere, the inner product <span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>a</sup></span> &middot; <span class="math-it">E<sub>j</sub><sup>t</sup></span> equals their cosine similarity. The training objective is:

<div class="formula-block">
&#x2112; = &minus;<span class="frac"><span class="frac-num">1</span><span class="frac-den">2<span class="math-it">N</span></span></span> &Sigma;<sub><span class="math-it">i</span>=1</sub><sup><span class="math-it">N</span></sup> <span style="font-size: 0.92em">[</span> log <span class="frac"><span class="frac-num">exp(<span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>a</sup></span> &middot; <span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>t</sup></span> / &tau;)</span><span class="frac-den">&Sigma;<sub><span class="math-it">j</span></sub> exp(<span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>a</sup></span> &middot; <span class="math-it">E<sub>j</sub><sup>t</sup></span> / &tau;)</span></span> + log <span class="frac"><span class="frac-num">exp(<span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>t</sup></span> &middot; <span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>a</sup></span> / &tau;)</span><span class="frac-den">&Sigma;<sub><span class="math-it">j</span></sub> exp(<span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>t</sup></span> &middot; <span class="math-it">E<sub>j</sub><sup>a</sup></span> / &tau;)</span></span> <span style="font-size: 0.92em">]</span>
</div>

<p class="muted">Reading it as code: the first log-term is the audio&rarr;text classification (for audio <span class="math-it">i</span>, the right answer among <span class="math-it">N</span> candidate captions is caption <span class="math-it">i</span>); the second is the symmetric text&rarr;audio classification. Without the symmetric term the text tower receives only weak gradient; under symmetric training both encoders are updated by the same loss magnitude per pair. &tau; is a <em>learnable</em> scalar &mdash; both papers parameterize it in log-space to keep it positive, with initialization values that differ in a revealing way (covered just below). Projections are L2-normalized <em>before</em> the inner product is taken; without this, the dot product would conflate similarity with vector magnitude and the loss would just push everything toward larger norms.</p>

### Why is this the right loss? The mutual-information lower bound

The InfoNCE loss is not arbitrary; it is provably a lower bound on the **mutual information** between the two views ([van den Oord et al., 2018](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1807.03748)). Specifically:

<div class="formula-block">
<span class="math-it">I</span>(<em>audio</em>; <em>text</em>) &nbsp;&ge;&nbsp; log <span class="math-it">N</span> &nbsp;&minus;&nbsp; &#x2112;<sub>InfoNCE</sub>
</div>

<p class="muted">Pushing the loss down pushes the bound up, so minimizing &#x2112; provably increases (the bound on) <span class="math-it">I</span>(audio; text). A consequence with practical bite: the bound is capped by <code>log N</code>. Doubling the batch size raises the ceiling by <code>log 2 &asymp; 0.69</code> nats. This is the formal reason contrastive methods are notoriously batch-size hungry &mdash; and why CLAP scales the batch from 768 to 2,304 to 4,608 as more corpora are mixed in. Empirically, doubling N improves zero-shot accuracy by 1&ndash;2 points across the board.</p>

<ContrastiveEmbedding />

<Callout type="insight" label="Geometric reading of the temperature">
	With unit-normalized embeddings, cosine similarity lives in [&minus;1, 1]. The softmax over similarities divided by &tau; defines a Boltzmann distribution on the unit sphere: every candidate is a "state" with energy &minus;<span class="math-it">E<sub>i</sub><sup>a</sup></span> &middot; <span class="math-it">E<sub>j</sub><sup>t</sup></span>. <strong>Small &tau; (~0.05)</strong> makes the distribution sharply peaked, so the loss is dominated by the single hardest negative &mdash; we are doing nearest-neighbor classification with extreme focus. <strong>Large &tau; (~1)</strong> flattens the distribution, so every candidate contributes roughly equally and the model averages over the long tail. CLAP keeps &tau; learnable; the model effectively tunes its own neighborhood size during training, typically converging to a small value once the geometry has settled.
</Callout>

<Callout type="gotcha" label="Intuition pump: the two pathological temperatures">
	<strong>&tau; &rarr; 0:</strong> The softmax becomes a hard argmax. If the matched caption is already the closest candidate, the gradient on every other negative is exactly zero. If it is not the closest, the loss is unbounded. Optimization becomes brittle and unstable. <br><br>
	<strong>&tau; &rarr; &infin;:</strong> The softmax becomes uniform. Every term in the loss is <code>log N</code> regardless of the model's predictions. The gradient w.r.t. the encoder weights is zero. The model never learns. <br><br>
	The sweet spot makes the softmax peaked enough to deliver meaningful gradient on the hardest negatives without zeroing out the long tail. Try predicting whether a model with &tau; fixed at 1 would converge before reading the answer (it would, but extremely slowly &mdash; it is effectively learning from soft negatives only).
</Callout>

<TemperatureSoftmax />

<Callout type="insight" label="MS-CLAP and LAION-CLAP make different &tau; choices">
	MS-CLAP initializes &tau; at <strong>0.007</strong> &mdash; deep into the sharp regime where the softmax is essentially nearest-neighbor classification from step zero. LAION-CLAP starts at &tau; &asymp; <strong>0.07</strong>, the same default as CLIP and roughly 10&times; softer. Drag the slider above between these two values to see what each commits the model to: MS-CLAP demands extreme focus on the single hardest negative right out of the gate, while LAION-CLAP keeps useful gradient on the long tail and lets the learnable parameter find equilibrium from a less aggressive starting point. Both work; they're different priors about how confident the model should be at initialization.
</Callout>

### Feature fusion: handling variable-length audio &nbsp;<span class="impl-pill">LAION-CLAP only</span>

LAION-CLAP's training set includes clips that run for minutes, but the audio encoder still expects a fixed-length input. Its solution is the **Attention Feature Fusion (AFF) module** &mdash; an attention-pooled aggregator that preserves both broad temporal context and local detail. (MS-CLAP, for comparison, simply sidestepped the problem by training only on **fixed 5-second clips** &mdash; clean, but discards anything longer.) The AFF algorithm is more involved than a simple chunk-and-pool. For a clip longer than 10 seconds:

<div class="formula-block" style="font-family: 'Quicksand', system-ui, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.6;">
<strong>1.</strong> Downsample the full clip to a single 10s tensor &rarr; <span class="math-it">X<sub>global</sub></span><br>
<strong>2.</strong> Sample three non-overlapping 10s windows from the front, middle, and back thirds of the original clip &rarr; three local tensors<br>
<strong>3.</strong> Pass all 4 tensors through the audio encoder's first stage<br>
<strong>4.</strong> Merge the three local features via a 2D-conv with temporal stride 3 &rarr; <span class="math-it">X<sub>local</sub></span><br>
<strong>5.</strong> Fuse: <span class="math-it">X<sub>fusion</sub></span> = &alpha; &middot; <span class="math-it">X<sub>global</sub></span> + (1 &minus; &alpha;) &middot; <span class="math-it">X<sub>local</sub></span>, where &alpha; is produced by the AFF block (a small attention module learning the mixing ratio per token)
</div>

<p class="muted">The intuition: the global view preserves broad temporal context (a 5-minute song's overall structure) while the three locals preserve fine-grained detail at full resolution; AFF lets the model adaptively weight the two depending on the content. Without fusion, the encoder must choose between coarse resolution (downsample everything) or losing context (random 10s crop). For clips shorter than 10 seconds, the input is simply repeated and padded; no fusion is applied.</p>

### Keyword-to-Caption augmentation &nbsp;<span class="impl-pill">LAION-CLAP only</span>

LAION-CLAP scales captioned-data availability by an order of magnitude over MS-CLAP &mdash; not by finding more captioned audio, but by *inventing* captions for the much larger label-only corpora. Much of the available audio data (AudioSet's 1.9M clips in particular) ships with sparse tag-style labels (a comma-separated list like <code>dog, barking, outdoor</code>) rather than fluent captions. CLAP turns these into training pairs by prompting a **pre-trained T5** with the keywords and the instruction *generate a caption from these keywords*, yielding outputs along the lines of *A dog is barking outdoors.* A small post-processing step replaces gendered terms (the words *man*, *woman*) with the neutral *person* to mitigate downstream gender bias amplification. The result is roughly **1.9M synthetic (audio, caption) pairs from AudioSet alone**, which dwarfs the genuinely captioned pool.

### Training data and hyperparameters

LAION-CLAP's full training corpus reaches approximately **2.5M (audio, caption) pairs** across three sources: **LAION-Audio-630K** (633,526 pairs, ~4,325 hours of in-the-wild web-scraped audio), **AudioCaps + Clotho** (~55K human-captioned pairs, the only genuinely high-quality captions in the mix), and **AudioSet** (1.9M label-to-caption pairs via the K2C augmentation above). Training runs for **45 epochs** with Adam (&beta;<sub>1</sub>=0.99, &beta;<sub>2</sub>=0.9), learning rate **1e&minus;4**, warmup followed by cosine decay. Batch size is scaled with corpus size: **768** for the smallest mix, **2,304** when LAION is included, **4,608** at full scale &mdash; a direct reflection of the <code>log N</code> bound discussed above. MS-CLAP, by contrast, used roughly **20&times; less data** and **40 epochs at lr 1e&minus;3** with batches as small as 32 &mdash; an instructive baseline for what the contrastive recipe can do with clean captions before scale enters the picture.

### What does CLAP actually let you do?

The reason all this engineering matters is the downstream interface it unlocks: once the encoders are trained, you can describe any sound in natural language and find it (or sounds like it) in any indexed library. No retraining per category.

<CLAPRetrieval />

<Callout type="gotcha" label="CLAP is not music-specific">
	CLAP is trained on general audio, with AudioSet, environmental sound corpora, and speech all present. It will happily distinguish "barking dog" from "car horn," but it does not know much about chord progressions or musical key. For music-specific tasks, music-targeted variants like MuLan or MuQ tend to do better. The fact that downstream music generation systems (AudioLDM2, Stable Audio) use CLAP anyway is a comment on data availability, not on optimality.
</Callout>

The downstream utility is broad and is the reason CLAP-style embeddings now appear in almost every recent audio generation system. Zero-shot classification: take the CLAP audio embedding, take the CLAP text embedding of each candidate class name ("dog barking," "piano," "rain"), pick the closest. Retrieval: build an index over a sound library and query it with a sentence. Conditioning: feed the CLAP text embedding to a diffusion model so that text prompts steer audio generation. None of these downstream uses require a fresh round of training; the representation does the work.

## MERT: Learning Music From Itself

[Li et al. (2024)](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2306.00107) take the position that aligning with text is the wrong starting point for music understanding, for two reasons. First, captions describe what *humans choose to say* about music, which is heavily biased toward genre, instrument, and mood, and almost never mentions key, harmonic function, or rhythmic structure; a representation aligned with that distribution will inherit its blind spots. Second, large-scale captioned music data is scarce compared to large-scale unlabeled music, and self-supervised approaches scale with raw audio hours rather than caption availability.

The architecture inherits from **HuBERT** in speech ([Hsu et al., 2021](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.07447)). Raw waveform at **24 kHz** is fed into a 7-layer convolutional feature extractor that downsamples to **75 Hz** (one frame per ~13.3 ms, matching EnCodec's tokenization rate exactly so the teachers and the encoder share a temporal grid). The frame sequence enters a Transformer encoder (**12 layers for MERT-95M-public**, **24 layers with Pre-LN for MERT-330M**). During training, frames are masked **HuBERT-style** &mdash; the MERT paper inherits the masking hyperparameters from HuBERT rather than restating them, so the numbers here are HuBERT's: roughly **8% of frames are sampled as starting indices** and each is expanded into a **10-frame span**, yielding approximately **50% of frames masked** in expectation. Masked positions are replaced with a learned mask embedding, and the model must predict properties of the masked frames from the surrounding context. What MERT changes is the *target* of that prediction.

<MaskingPattern />

