### The acoustic teacher: EnCodec RVQ-VAE

The acoustic teacher is a pre-trained **EnCodec** residual vector-quantized autoencoder ([Défossez et al., 2022](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2210.13438)). EnCodec processes the original (unmasked) audio and emits at each frame a stack of **K = 8 codebook indices**, where each codebook has **1024 entries**. This factorized representation can express 1024<sup>8</sup> &asymp; 10<sup>24</sup> distinct combinations per frame, more than enough to reconstruct the waveform on decoding. MERT trains a per-codebook classification head on top of the transformer encoder. For each masked frame <span class="math-it">t</span> in the masked set <span class="math-it">M</span> and each codebook <span class="math-it">k</span> from 1 to 8, the encoder must predict the right index out of 1024:

<div class="formula-block">
&#x2112;<sub>acoustic</sub> = &minus; &Sigma;<sub><span class="math-it">t</span> &isin; <span class="math-it">M</span></sub> &Sigma;<sub><span class="math-it">k</span>=1</sub><sup>8</sup> log <span class="math-it">p<sub>f<sub>k</sub></sub></span>(<span class="math-it">z<sub>t,k</sub></span> &nbsp;|&nbsp; <span class="math-it">x</span>&prime;, <span class="math-it">t</span>)
</div>

<p class="muted">where <span class="math-it">x</span>&prime; is the masked input sequence, <span class="math-it">z<sub>t,k</sub></span> is the ground-truth code index from running EnCodec on the unmasked audio at frame <span class="math-it">t</span> in codebook <span class="math-it">k</span>, and <span class="math-it">f<sub>k</sub></span> is the prediction head for codebook <span class="math-it">k</span>. This is identical in form to HuBERT's loss but with codes drawn from EnCodec rather than k-means on MFCCs. The paper also explored a k-means alternative (300 centroids on log-mel + 200 centroids on chroma, joint cluster space = 60,000 classes); EnCodec proved more effective. Any feature in the encoder that helps minimize &#x2112;<sub>acoustic</sub> must by construction preserve enough information to identify which of 1024 acoustic prototypes &mdash; spectral shape, transient pattern, broad timbre &mdash; the masked frame belongs to in each of 8 parallel quantizations.</p>

<RVQCodebookLadder />

### The musical teacher: CQT regression

The musical teacher is the **Constant-Q Transform** of the original audio. The CQT differs from a mel-spectrogram in that its frequency bins are spaced *logarithmically*, with one bin per semitone (or a fraction thereof), which means harmonics of any pitch land at fixed, semantically meaningful positions independent of the fundamental. MERT trains a separate prediction head <span class="math-it">f<sub>cqt</sub></span> to regress the CQT magnitudes at masked positions under an L2 loss:

<div class="formula-block">
&#x2112;<sub>musical</sub> = &Sigma;<sub><span class="math-it">t</span> &isin; <span class="math-it">M</span></sub> &Vert; <span class="math-it">z<sub>cqt,t</sub></span> &minus; <span class="math-it">f<sub>cqt</sub></span>(<span class="math-it">x</span>&prime;)<sub><span class="math-it">t</span></sub> &Vert;<sub>2</sub>
</div>

<p class="muted">where <span class="math-it">z<sub>cqt,t</sub></span> is the CQT bin vector at frame <span class="math-it">t</span> computed on the unmasked audio. This is regression, not classification: the head outputs a continuous vector and is trained to land near the target rather than choose among quantized categories. The choice matters &mdash; quantizing CQT would discard the magnitude information that distinguishes a forte from a piano, and would reintroduce the pitch-blurring that motivated using CQT in the first place.</p>

<SpectrogramComparison />

The two losses are combined with a scalar weight &alpha; (the paper sweeps and finds **&alpha; = 1** optimal):

<div class="formula-block">
&#x2112;<sub>total</sub> = &alpha; &middot; &#x2112;<sub>acoustic</sub> + &#x2112;<sub>musical</sub>
</div>

<Callout type="insight" label="Why two teachers?">
	The dual-teacher trick is the core design move and it is worth dwelling on. The acoustic teacher (EnCodec) cares about audio fidelity; the musical teacher (CQT) cares about musical content. These objectives conflict in interesting ways: a model that perfectly reconstructs acoustic codes can be wrong about pitch (EnCodec's perceptual loss tolerates sub-semitone errors that catastrophically change the music); a model that perfectly reconstructs CQT can be wrong about timbre. Forcing the encoder to satisfy both means the resulting representation cannot afford to drop either kind of information.
</Callout>

<Callout type="gotcha" label="Intuition pump: remove one teacher">
	The paper's ablations make the dependency explicit. <strong>Remove the CQT teacher (acoustic only):</strong> the k-means-teacher variant's key-detection accuracy collapses from <strong>65.0%</strong> down to <strong>55.1%</strong>, because the acoustic codes by themselves don't penalize pitch errors that are perceptually small. <strong>Remove the EnCodec teacher (CQT only):</strong> instrument and singer identification suffer, because CQT discards the phase, transient, and broadband noise structure that distinguishes a clarinet from a saxophone playing the same pitch. The headline 330M numbers degrade meaningfully in both directions &mdash; before reading the ablation table, try predicting which kind of downstream task would suffer more from each removal. (Hint: think about what each teacher's loss is structurally blind to.)
</Callout>

### Scale and training

The two principal model sizes are:

<div class="formula-block" style="font-family: 'Quicksand', system-ui, sans-serif; font-style: normal; font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7;">
<strong>MERT-95M-public:</strong> 12 transformer layers &middot; 95M parameters &middot; trained on <strong>910 hours</strong> of Music4All (the released checkpoint; the paper's internal 95M used a ~1K-hour subset of the larger corpus)<br>
<strong>MERT-330M:</strong> 24 transformer layers with Pre-LN &middot; 330M parameters &middot; trained on <strong>~160K hours</strong> of mixed CC-licensed and internet-mined music
</div>

<p class="muted">Batch sizes are expressed in audio-hours per step (a useful convention for music SSL): roughly <strong>1.5 hours per batch</strong> for the 95M models, <strong>5.5 hours per batch</strong> for the 330M. At 75 Hz, 5.5 hours corresponds to approximately <strong>1.5 million frames per batch</strong> &mdash; large enough to make EnCodec teacher precomputation and on-disk caching non-trivial. Pre-LN was specifically introduced in the 330M variant because the original Post-LN HuBERT recipe diverged at this scale, a hard-won engineering lesson the paper documents in the appendix.</p>

### Evaluation: MARBLE and the probing protocol

After pretraining, the encoder is evaluated on the **MARBLE benchmark** ([Yuan et al., 2023](https://github.com/a43992899/MARBLE-Benchmark)) plus separate evaluations covering genre classification, emotion recognition, key detection, beat tracking, source separation, and singer identification. The protocol is **probing**: the MERT weights are frozen and a small head is trained per task. The head is not always linear &mdash; the paper's default probe is an **MLP with one hidden layer of 512 units and 0.25 dropout**, trained with batch size 64. Hyperparameter search is limited to a small learning-rate grid spanning <code>1e&minus;4</code> through <code>1e&minus;2</code>. The 330M model achieves state-of-the-art across most tasks at the time of publication, including notably strong results on the pitch-sensitive tasks where prior masked-modeling work without a musical teacher had lagged.

<Callout type="gotcha" label="Probing vs. fine-tuning">
	MERT's headline numbers come from frozen encoder + MLP probe, not full fine-tuning. This is on purpose: it is a fair test of how much musical information the <em>representation itself</em> captures, independent of how much can be coaxed out by gradient-updating every weight. But the numbers are not directly comparable to fully fine-tuned task-specific models elsewhere in the literature, and a representation that probes well does not always fine-tune best (sometimes the &quot;smoothing&quot; introduced by the probe hides usable signal). Always read the eval protocol before reading the table.
</Callout>

### What MERT lets you ask about a clip

Once the encoder is trained, the workflow is: feed a clip through MERT (frozen), grab the resulting frame-level features, and train a tiny task head on top. The same representation supports very different questions in parallel.

<MERTProbes />

## How They Connect

CLAP and MERT both seek a general-purpose audio representation, but they make almost-mirrored design decisions, and the resulting embeddings have correspondingly mirrored strengths.

