		<text x="450" y="58" text-anchor="middle" fill="#c8611a" font-size="9" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif" font-weight="500">masked acoustic modeling</text>
		<line x1="350" y1="68" x2="550" y2="68" stroke="#dde0e6" stroke-width="0.6"/>
		<text x="350" y="84" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="9" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif">Signal:</text>
		<text x="350" y="96" fill="#e07020" font-size="9.5" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif">masked frames (audio only)</text>
		<text x="350" y="116" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="9" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif">Strength:</text>
		<text x="350" y="128" fill="#e07020" font-size="9.5" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif">pitch / harmony features</text>
		<text x="350" y="148" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="9" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif">Weakness:</text>
		<text x="350" y="160" fill="#e07020" font-size="9.5" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif">no language interface</text>
		<text x="350" y="180" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="9" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif">Used by:</text>
		<text x="350" y="192" fill="#e07020" font-size="9.5" font-family="Quicksand, system-ui, sans-serif">MIR probes, music tagging, MARBLE</text>
	</svg>
</div>

The most useful way to read the pair is to ask, for any given downstream task, *which kind of supervisory signal would have been most informative during pretraining?* If the task involves matching audio to natural language ("retrieve clips that sound joyful," "label by genre using a free-text vocabulary"), CLAP's training distribution maps directly. If the task involves musical structure that captioners rarely mention (chord recognition, key detection, beat tracking, instrument fingerprinting), MERT's frame-level acoustic supervision captures it more faithfully. Several recent systems combine both, using CLAP for the conditioning interface and MERT for the encoder backbone; the two are complementary in production even though they compete in the literature.

It is also worth noting how this pair maps onto the parallel debate in vision. CLIP (contrastive cross-modal) and DINO / MAE (self-supervised single-modal) emerged at roughly the same time for the same reason, and the field has not so much resolved the debate as accepted that both representations have their place. CLAP and MERT are the audio-side echo. The next several years of work in audio representation learning will likely follow the vision template: hybridization (use both signals together), distillation (compress the bigger model into a smaller deployable one), and progressively more music-specific second modalities (lyric-aligned text, score-aligned MIDI, performance metadata).

## Further Reading

CLAP and MERT are entry points into much larger families. If either clicked, here's how to navigate the literature next.

### Beyond CLAP: variants and the music-specific cousins

The contrastive audio-text recipe has been extended in several productive directions. The most important pointer for a music-AI audience is <strong>MuLan</strong>, which is essentially "CLAP, but music-specific and at 44M-clip scale" &mdash; it's the audio encoder behind Google's MusicLM and the most direct music-domain analog of what we covered today. <strong>MuQ-MuLan</strong> is its 2025 successor and currently the SOTA music-CLAP.

<div class="resources-grid">
	<ResourceLink href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2208.12415" category="Paper · ISMIR 2022" categoryType="paper" label="MuLan: A Joint Embedding of Music Audio and Natural Language" host="Huang et al. (Google) — 44M music clips, audio encoder behind MusicLM" />
	<ResourceLink href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.01108" category="Paper · 2025" categoryType="paper" label="MuQ &amp; MuQ-MuLan: Music SSL with Mel-RVQ Teachers" host="Zhu et al. — current music-CLAP SOTA, beats MERT with much less data" />
	<ResourceLink href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.05767" category="Paper · 2023" categoryType="paper" label="Natural Language Supervision for General-Purpose Audio Representations (MS-CLAP 2023)" host="Elizalde et al. — multi-task encoder + autoregressive text decoder, 4.6M pairs" />
	<ResourceLink href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.08753" category="Paper · ICLR 2024" categoryType="paper" label="CompA: Compositional Reasoning in Audio-Language Models" host="Ghosh et al. — CLAP-family models are near-random on compositional tasks; this fixes it" />
	<ResourceLink href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.17806" category="Paper · 2024" categoryType="paper" label="T-CLAP: Temporal-Enhanced CLAP" host="Yuan et al. — targets temporal/event-order reasoning, a documented CLAP weakness" />
</div>

### Beyond MERT: other paths to music SSL

MERT is one of several approaches to self-supervised music understanding. The most useful contrasts are with <strong>MusicFM</strong> (which argues you don't need a learned tokenizer at all &mdash; random-projection quantization works fine) and <strong>JukeMIR</strong> (which argues the right move is to skip SSL entirely and reuse a large generative model's hidden states as features). <strong>MAP-Music2Vec</strong> is MERT's direct predecessor from the same group and shows the lineage. <strong>MULE</strong> is the strongest non-transformer non-masked baseline.

<div class="resources-grid">
	<ResourceLink href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.03318" category="Paper · ICASSP 2024" categoryType="paper" label="MusicFM: A Foundation Model for Music Informatics" host="Won, Hung, Le — BEST-RQ-style with random-projection quantizer (no learned tokenizer)" />
	<ResourceLink href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2107.05677" category="Paper · ISMIR 2021" categoryType="paper" label="Codified Audio Language Modeling Learns Useful Representations for MIR (JukeMIR)" host="Castellon, Donahue, Liang — frozen Jukebox features for MIR" />
	<ResourceLink href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2212.02508" category="Paper · 2022" categoryType="paper" label="MAP-Music2Vec: Music Audio Self-Supervised Learning" host="Li et al. — data2vec adapted to music; MERT's direct predecessor from the M-A-P group" />
	<ResourceLink href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03799" category="Paper · 2022" categoryType="paper" label="MULE: Supervised &amp; Unsupervised Learning of Audio Representations for Music" host="McCallum et al. — SF-NFNet-F0 + contrastive on 117k hours; standard MARBLE baseline" />
</div>

